[normal]HE.18 Substantial force had been used in one case to take a pregnant woman resisting removal to depa
[normal]rtures. The woman was not moved using approved techniques. She was placed in a wheelchair to assist her to the departures area.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]When she resisted, it was tipped-up with staff holding her feet. At one point she slipped down from the chair and the risk of i
[normal]njury to the unborn child was
[normal] 
[normal]significant. There is no safe way to use force against a pregnant woman, and to initiate it for the purpose of removal is to take an unacceptable risk.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The UK Border Agency would prefer that pregnant women, vulnerable adults and under 18s who 
[normal]form part of family groups in Cedars left the UK voluntarily and compliantly. It would not be 
[normal]practical to consider a blanket 
[normal]ban on the use of physical intervention on pregnant women and under 18s as this might encourage non-compliance and render the Agency unable to maintain effective immigration controls.
