[normal]&#xa0;[bold]20. In an article 8 case ... the ultimate question for the appellate immigration authority is whether the refusal of leave to enter or remain, in circumstances where the life of the family cannot reasonab
[normal]ly be expected to be 
[normal]enjoyed elsewhere, taking full account of all considerations weighing in favour of the refusal, prejudices the family life of the applicant in a manner sufficiently serious to amount to a breach of the fundamental right protected by ar
[normal]ticle 8. If the answer to this question is affirmative, the refusal is unlawful and the authority must so decide. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The search for a hard-edged or bright-line rule to be 
[normal]applied to the generality of cases is incompatible with the difficult evaluative exercise which article 8 requires.
