[normal]“[T]he proposal would deny payment in a case with real merit but that just failed to get permission. … The proposal carries the danger 
[normal]that it will act as a barrier to access to justice as lawyers and other advice providers will err on the side of caution where the appeal is ambitious but not one with little or no merit – perhaps only bringing cases with a predicted 70/30 or more prospect
[normal] of success, when the proposal intends to remove funding only where the case fails at 51/49 or less.”
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]…[bold]especially in t
[normal]he early stages, the defendant is likely to have more information to enable it to assess the merits of a claim. Indeed, most of us have had experience of being instructed to defend government decisions despite advising that the prospects of doing so are co
[normal]nsiderably below 50%. Sometimes we will have been proven wrong. No one has ever suggested that, in such cases, government bodies should be barred from defending a claim for judicial review. To take such an approach would quickly make the work of government
[normal] impossible. Government lawyers do not undertake their work on the basis that they will only be paid if they have accurately predicted the outcome of the litigation. To require this of those acting on legal aid is, in effect, to severely cut their rates.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Since the majority of successful claims are conceded pre-permission, to use permission as the test for whether payment is made may well reduce real rates even further. We are also concerned that the proposal will be 
[normal]counter-productive; there will be many m
[normal]ore disputes about pre-permission costs, which will require substantial public money to resolve.
[normal] 
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The superficially attractive reason is that it will inhibit the making of long-shot or speculative claims at 
[normal]public expense, but it is supported by no evidence, and the argument advanced in support of it – that the claimant’s lawyer ‘is in the best position to know the strength of their client’s case’ – displays a depressing degree of ignorance about how judicial
[normal] review works. More often than not, it is the defendant authority which holds most of the relevant cards, and in many cases it holds on to them for longer than it is supposed to, either because there is too little time for proper disclosure of documents or
[normal] because sitting tight affords the best hope that the claim will go away. The departmental calculation is that indigent claimants’ lawyers will be deterred from taking on all but
[normal] 
[normal]sure-fire claims. In proposing that other claimants can be left to their own 
[normal]devices without injustice, the paper makes no attempt to confront the consequences: a plethora of claims
[normal] 
[normal]made by litigants
[normal] in 
[normal]person, clogging up the courts as judges try to discern arguable points in the chaos of paper, and costing public authorities larg
[normal]e sums in irrecoverable costs as they attempt to respond to such claims.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal][I]t is vital for the Ministry to appreciate that any changes which are made to reduce legal aid and cut the cost of litigation are likely to have a kno
[normal]ck-on effect on the cost of the courts. Less legal aid means more unrepresented litigants and worse lawyers, which will lead to longer hearings and more judge-time.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The requirement that a claim can only be funded where it meets a merits test already imposes a significant discipline on clai
[normal]mant lawyers which is not, at least in any formal sense, imposed on defendants to judicial review. The figures quoted at paragraphs 3.65-8 of the Consultation Paper do not suggest that legal aid is being granted in significant numbers of unmeritorious case
[normal]s, and that is not our experience as Treasury Counsel defending such claims. ….
